  4.1.2 Drop Point Estimation
  
  $$
  (1 2 \\mathrm {x} N)
  $$
  
  The goal in drop point estimation is to find the points in a
  track where the “drop” happens. The term “drop” is typically used in the context of specific types of electronic
  dance music, and refers to the point(s) in time where a
  drastic change in the song occurs following a large build.
  In our context, we are looking for points in a song where
  an exceptionally interesting event occurs. Rather than take
  a content-based solution similar to \[17\], we use a crowdsourced approach following from the work described in
  P. Lamere’s blog10. Lamere computes the points where
  users moved (scrubbed) the playhead while listening to a
  track. Typically users tend to move the playhead towards
  the most interesting points in the track. Figure 4 (top)
  shows an example of the aggregated playhead scrubbing
  data (blue) for Skrillex: “First of the Year”. The large
  peak occurring around 66 seconds accurately marks the
  first big drop, and the second smaller peak around 145 seconds marks the second big drop.
  To identify these peak locations, we use a standard peak
  
  onds marks the second big drop.
  To identify these peak locations, we use a standard peak
  picking approach from the onset detection literature \[1\]:
  an adaptive threshold (shown in green) is computing using a median filter, then a detection function subtracts the
  adaptive threshold from the normalized scrub ratio and selects its peaks, as shown in Figure 4 (bottom). Choosing
  the closest downbeat that occurs before each resulting peak
  gives us our final drop index D. Note that in Figure 4 there
  is a small peak near the start of the track which is not a
  significant musical point. We correct for this by removing
  peaks that occur within the first 15 seconds of the track.
  
  Figure 4: Drop point estimation intermediate steps for
  Skrillex: “First of the Year (Equinox)”. Top: Normalized scrub ratio and adaptive threshold. Bottom: Detection function and detected drop points. The first peak in
  the detection function is not a drop point because it occurs
  within the first 15 seconds of the track.
  
